# Company brief

Single source of truth for what this company is, what it sells, and who
it sells to. Every agent loads this at start-up. `/teamfuse-init` writes
the live version as `agents/sop/company.md` from the answers the
operator provides during bootstrap. Safe to edit by hand later; changes
propagate on each agent's next `/clear`.

## What the company does

<one to three sentences on the company's mission, the problem it
exists to solve, and why it is worth solving. Written in plain
prose so every agent can quote from it verbatim in user-facing
copy, release notes, and analyst digests.>

## The product

<one to three sentences describing the product itself: shape
(SaaS, CLI, library, physical good, service), core capabilities,
and what a user does with it on a typical day. Keep it concrete.>

## Who it is for

<one to three sentences on the target customer. Role, team size,
industry, budget band, pain point. If there is a clear
anti-customer (who this is NOT for), name them here too.>

## Positioning one-liner

<the single sentence marketing uses in landing-page copy,
launch posts, and external pitches. Marketing's `CLAUDE.md`
also references this verbatim via the `<product-positioning>`
placeholder.>

## How agents should use this

* Every agent reads this file via `../sop/company.md` before acting on
  ambiguous work. When a card says "draft a release note", this file
  defines the voice and the audience.
* Marketing copies the positioning one-liner verbatim. No rewrites
  unless the operator updates this file.
* PM uses "Who it is for" to sanity-check new Backlog proposals. If a
  proposal does not serve the named audience, reject or re-scope.
* Analyst frames every metric digest in terms of the mission above. A
  number that does not tie back to the mission does not belong in the
  digest.
* Eng uses the product description to pick defaults when a card leaves
  acceptance criteria ambiguous.
